    <h2>6. Data Preprocessing</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Handled missing values and duplicates</li>
      <li>Converted numeric formats and date fields</li>
      <li>Encoded state names if needed</li>
      <li>Derived recovery metrics (e.g., recovery rate)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>  <section>
    <h2>7. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Univariate: Distribution of theft and recovery amounts by year/state</li>
      <li>Bivariate: Theft vs Recovery correlation, heatmaps, line trends</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Key Insights:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>States with low recovery efficiency</li>
      <li>Yearly improvement or decline trends</li>
    </ul>
  </section>  <section>
    <h2>8. Key Findings & Insights</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Certain states have &gt;70% case recovery, others &lt;30%</li>
      <li>High-value thefts often have poor recovery rates</li>
    </ul>
  </section>  <section>
    <h2>9. Recommendations</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Focus resources on low-performing states</li>
      <li>Improve tracking of high-value property theft</li>
      <li>Use analytics for year-on-year policy adjustments</li>
    </ul>
  </section>  <section>
